k0">;The point of perpetual stew, otherwise known as “forever soup”, is very much in the name.烹饪从未停止，因为食材会根据需要补充。食用前确保混合物滚烫，可减少食物中毒的可能性；一旦温度达到 74°C (165°F)，大多数有害细菌就会死亡。 Rauwerda 女士表示，在她任职 60 天期间，没有人生病。 </p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;Social media have heralded a revival of interest in the stew as a meal both cheap and delicious. In 2020 a recipe by Alison Roman, a bestselling food writer, advised using <a href="https://www.economist.com/1843/2019/09/06/why-chickpea-flour-is-so-chic">;chickpeas</a>; and coconut milk;它迅速走红并赢得了#thestew 的明确绰号。 The dish is often thought of as a warming and starchy staple in winter, but search for “summer stew” and you will find scores of recipes.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;Stew has a long-simmering lineage. In medieval Europe peasants would make a pottage (on the heartier side, with a thick consistency) or a <i>;pot-au-feu</i>; (a more liquid soup), incorporating whatever foods and flavourings they could afford and were seasonally available.它全年都被消费。 According to Lucy Worsley, a historian, 76% of a <a href="https://www.economist.com/culture/2024/02/21/is-everything-you-assumed-about-the-middle-ages-wrong">;medieval</a>; labourer's calories came from bread and pottage.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;Some perpetual stews have earned renown.据报道，一艘法国船从 15 世纪一直航行到第二次世界大战。 War also put a stop to an <i>;oden </i>;(fishcake broth) that had reportedly been enjoyed at Otafuku, a restaurant in Tokyo, since 1916; a successor, still going strong, was established in 1945.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;At Wattana Panich, an eatery in <a href="https://www.economist.com/1843/2017/01/19/bangkoks-joyous-cuisine">;Bangkok</a>;, a noodle soup with beef has been cooking for half a century in a gargantuan pan that stands five feet wide and two and a half feet deep.店主 Nattapong Kaweeantawong 每天添加近 70 公斤牛肉，并持续搅拌成香草、香料和根的浓缩混合物。 It, too, has excited interest (as well as taste buds): a video by Winela World, a travel influencer, has almost half a million likes on TikTok.</p>;<div class="adComponent_advert__kPVUI adComponent_incontent__boSCu adComponent_hidden__Dp0GM css-0 e1cbnkh80 ">;<div>;<div id="econ-2" class="adComponent_adcontainer__eooQr">;</div>;</div>;</div>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;除了新奇之外，吃一碗还有两个原因。一是品味。汤可能是稀薄的，但连续的汤会随着时间的推移而产生浓郁的味道。 Wattana Panich 汤的评论称赞它像肉汁一样，既“诱人”又“味道爆炸”。 </p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;The other is communality.浓汤是在壁炉上方的大锅中制作的，通常在家庭的主要起居区：这象征着食物在将家人和朋友聚集在一起方面发挥着核心作用。 Paul Scarron, a French poet, wrote in the 17th century that pottage “delights our bodies,/and yet more our souls”. </p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;In the atomised 21st century, the idea of sharing a meal with your neighbour is more remote than ever. But Ms Rauwerda found that her <a href="https://www.economist.com/culture/2024/03/15/how-worried-should-people-be-about-generation-z">;Gen Z</a>; peers delighted in the social and collaborative aspect of the perpetual stew. “会有一些顽固分子每周都会来，并坚持到最后，”她说。其中两人现在处于恋爱关系中。当罐子耗尽时，Rauwerda 女士估计她已经喂饱了大约 100 人。毫无疑问，他们渴望更多。正如有人在 TikTok 上写道：“炖菜团队什么时候再次聚会？” <span class="ufinish">;■</span>;</p>;</div>; https://www.economist.com/culture/2024/04/04/perpetual-stew-an-ancient-way-of-cooking-has-won-gen-z-fans /content/e6jjd3lrsuci9cc1id7j070luogv7bqt Thu, 04 Apr 2024 11:12:57 GMT
